title: Story - My Mother's Garden
contentMarkdown: Note: I wrote this flash fiction story for a contest some years ago. I didn't win, but this story remains one of my personal favourites. My Mother’s Garden It had always been my mother’s dream to have a garden of her own. She’d been a city-dweller all her life, moving from one rented flat to another, perpetually a few floors above ground, where her horticultural pursuits were limited to small potted plants in the balcony. So, in her forty-second year, when the bank finally approved Baba’s home loan, she insisted that we buy a house with a garden. Baba, who’d been eyeing a 2BHK in a swanky new complex in South Calcutta, was appalled. “Everyone wishes to move up in life,” he said, shaking his head with exasperation. “But you want to go down?” This was followed by endless debates and arguments and pleading, but Ma stood her ground, and eventually Baba had to relent. After a lot of searching, they were able to find a ground floor apartment in a sleepy North Calcutta suburb, with a patch of dirt out front that was too dry for even grass to grow on it. “It’s not much right now,” Ma said, picking up a fistful of soil, “but with a little care and effort, I’ll turn it into a green paradise.” Her words, however, proved to be incorrect. Six months later, her ‘garden’ was as arid as the day we’d moved in. It wasn’t for lack of effort either. Ma must’ve spent hundreds of hours digging and composting the soil, pouring countless bags of fertilizer and oceans of water into it, all to no avail. On Sundays, despite my father’s protests, she would make him drive her to the local nursery to buy seeds and saplings of different varieties. But the seeds would stubbornly refuse to sprout, and the saplings would wither and die within a few days. Whatever the opposite of a green thumb was, my mother had it. This repeated failure in growing anything at all frustrated her to no end. Finally, one morning, after seeing an estimate of how much she’d spent on supplies, Ma came to the decision that the garden was a lost cause. “Let’s pave it with bricks and pour concrete over it,” she said with a sense of resignation. “That way, at least we can have a patio.” Surprisingly, it was Baba who persuaded her not to give up. “These things take time,” he said. “The next one you plant will be successful, I can feel it.” Seeing Baba’s change of heart, Ma decided to give it one last try. My sister had been germinating tomato seeds in small cups for a science project, which Ma carefully replanted in her garden, and waited. Like the others before them, these plants did not survive either— all but one. To Ma’s delight, a single hardy sapling persisted, developing little by little until it was a few inches tall. Ma tended to it with enormous care, gently watering it just the right amount everyday, pruning its dead leaves, and shading it from excess sunlight. Slowly, but surely, it grew, and Ma planted a stick in the ground to support the stem. A month later, it flowered, and a month after that, Ma served us her very first homegrown tomato. She cut it into four equal pieces, and we ate it raw, savoring its tart ripeness, so full of taste. No one was prouder of this single tomato than Ma herself. With a gleam in her eye, she announced that next on her agenda were carrots. I glanced at Baba across the table, who avoided my gaze. We’d never had a second discussion about the time I’d heard a disturbance from Ma’s garden in the middle of the night, and had gone out to find him crouched in the mud, pouring something dark out of a small sack. “It’s peat moss,” he’d explained, after seeing that it was only me. “The soil is too alkaline, this will make it acidic enough for the tomatoes.” “I don’t think Ma will be happy to hear that you’ve been messing about in her garden.” “Who’s going to tell her?” ![image1](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
